Question 1:Why does a model trained on flowers/vehicles get good at your categories faster?

From the gist of how i get it is that when it comes to CNN and its layers the first few layers can go about learning what stuff like edges are, or fur, or color, what are lines etc. whilst maybe in the middle it would say what are curves and corners, what is this shape, is it rough? etc. whilst the very end of it all is where it finalizes thinking that the patterns like oh its green, doesnt have wheels, has petals it must be a flower. 

So now how does this have anything to do with the categories i took? well its all in those beginning and middle layers. How i like to think of it is that making a new model from scratch is like teaching a baby what a car is or what a plant is, how to know if it is a plant or a car, or if its a dog or a cat and so on. 

The baby would have to learn from scratch like oh it has ears, it has certain features and sometimes it might mistake the two but with more data they would understand it better.
Now take it that the ai gets past that stage already of having to learn lines,edges,fur etc. Now learning how to tell those signs becomes a lot faster and a lot more accurate.
since now there isnt a need for it to learn all of that and make mistakes because of those missing knowledge. Thats what resnet50 does since it already learned all of these things it helps my ai understand those things and skip having to learn all of it and go straight to figuring out the end layer which would be like how to tell the difference between the animals

so the gist of it is that the beginning is quite general making it useful to many ai's.




Question 2: How many inputs does a 1×1 kernel get after a conv2d layer with 32 kernels?
so the short answer to this would just be that its 32 inputs thats how many it takes but just to better understand it from how i get it is that with 1x1 it just reads everything in every spatial position so after 32 output channels it would just take 32 inputs each without any spatial mixing and this is just so that changing numbers of channels can be done cheaply.

I know that resnet uses this specifically so that it first reduces the channel count and then the 3x3 conv can do its spatial work on some smaller representation which then it goes back to its 1x1 and goes back to its origianl channel amount which in the end makes things cheaper/affordable to trian